{"title_page": "The Dan Le Batard Show with Stugotz", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n| show_name       = The Dan Le Batard Show with Stugotz\n| image           = File:Dan Le Batard Show logo.png\n| imagesize       =\n| caption         =\n| other_names     =\n| format          = [[Sports]] [[Talk show|talk]]\n| runtime         = 4 hours\n| country         = [[United States]]\n| language        = [[English language|English]]\n| home_station    = [[WAXY (AM)|WAXY]] (2004 \u2013 August 2nd, 2019, August 5th, 2019 (local hour))<br>[[WQAM]] (August 5th, 2019\u2013present)<br>[[ESPN Radio]] (2013\u2013present)\n| television      = [[Fusion TV]] (2015\u20132016)<br>[[ESPNU]] (2015\u20132018)<br>[[ESPNEWS]] (2018\u2013present)\n| presenter       =\n| starring        = [[Dan Le Batard]] <br> [[Jon \"Stugotz\" Weiner]]\n| announcer       = Gonzalo \"Papi\" Le Batard\n| creator         =\n| writer          =\n| director        =\n| professional cat herders        = Mike Ryan Ruiz, Roy Bellamy, Billy \"Guillermo\" Gil, Chris \"I'm Chris Cote ESPN\" Cote, Allyson Turner\n| executive_producer = \n| narrated        =\n| record_location = [[Miami Beach]], [[Florida]]\n| first_aired     = September 1, 2004\n| last_aired      = present\n| num_series      =\n| num_episodes    =\n| audio_format    =\n| opentheme       = A mashup mix featuring the ''[[Blade (film)|Blade]]'' theme, [[Brooklyn Bounce]]'s \"This is the Real Bass,\" and [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]]'s \"[[Party Up (Up in Here)]],\" featuring clips offering signature moments from the show's various personalities.\n| endtheme        = Gonzalo Le Batard saying, \"We will talk to you ma\u00f1ana, this has been the Dan Le Batard Show on ESPN Radio\" and [[Gregg Popovich]] saying \"We live in a racist country.\"\n| website         = [http://espn.go.com/espnradio/show?showId=danlebatard The Dan Le Batard Show on ESPN Radio]<br />[http://www.theticketmiami.com/dan-lebatard/ www.theticketmiami.com]\n| podcast         = [http://lebatard.790theticket.libsynpro.com/rss Podcast RSS]<br />[http://espn.go.com/espnradio/podcast/archive?id=9941853 Podcast on ESPN Radio]}}\n\n'''''The Dan Le Batard Show with Stugotz''''' is a [[sports radio|sports]] [[talk radio]] show hosted by [[Dan Le Batard]] and [[Jon \"Stugotz\" Weiner]] and broadcast on [[WQAM|WQAM \u201c560 The Joe\u201d]] in South Florida and [[ESPN Radio]] affiliates nationwide. The show was heard locally Monday through Friday from 9 AM to 1 PM ET on [[WAXY (AM)|WAXY]] AM 790 \"The Ticket\" until August 5th, 2019. It is now heard locally and nationally on ESPN Radio and [[ESPNEWS]] from 10 AM to 1 PM (prior to April 2, 2018, the television simulcast was aired on [[ESPNU]]).  The show features commentary on the day's sports news, perspective on other news stories, interviews with sports analysts and sports figures, as well as a generous blend of pop culture and listener interaction.  The hosts are known for their self-deprecating humor, which carries over onto the show through running jokes. Le Batard and Stugotz interact throughout the show with executive producer Mike Ryan, show booker Allyson Turner, and fellow producers Roy Bellamy, Billy \"Guillermo\" Gil, and Chris \"Fats and Info\" Cote, collectively nicknamed the Shipping Container Filled with Frightened Refugees. The show commonly refers to themselves as a \"marching band to nowhere<nowiki>''</nowiki> and a <nowiki>''</nowiki>flying saucer of BS<nowiki>''</nowiki> \n\nCurrently, Le Batard and Stugotz are joined on-air by Greg Cote of [[The Miami Herald]] on Tuesdays, and additional ESPN personalities (including [[Sarah Spain]], [[Domonique Foxworth]], [[Mina Kimes]] and others) make regular guest hosting appearances.\n\nAfter running for nine years on local radio, The Dan Le Batard Show debuted on ESPN Radio on September 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dan Le Batard launches ESPN Radio show Monday |url=http://www.awfulannouncing.com/2013/september/dan-le-batard-launches-espn-radio-show-monday.html |author=Matt Yoder |work=Awful Announcing |publisher=Bloguin |date=27 September 2013 |accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, It was announced that the show would be televised on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]] starting May 19, 2015.<ref>http://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/111576430949/espns-dan-le-batard-to-bring-his-signature-voice</ref> After the departure of [[Colin Cowherd]] from ESPN, the network moved the time slot of the show into the 10 AM to 1 PM slot formerly occupied by [[The Herd with Colin Cowherd]], and moved the live simulcast to [[ESPNU]], with the Fusion broadcast shifting to tape delay from 1 to 4 PM. On May 18, 2016, Fusion aired the show for the last time as the year-long contract with ABC/Disney was expired and was not renewed. The TV portion of the show then remained solely on ESPNU afterwards with the show airing live from 10 AM to 1 PM with no outlet for a tape-delay. On January 10, 2017, the final hour of the show began simulcasting on [[ESPN2]], but in July 2017, the show's final hour returned to airing on ESPNU. On April 2, 2018, the show's simulcast moved to [[ESPNEWS]].\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Tim Hardaway's homophobic comments ===\nOn February 14, 2007, the week of the [[2007 NBA All-Star Game]], former [[Miami Heat]] player [[Tim Hardaway]] appeared on the show.  When asked if he would be accepting of a gay teammate, such as retired NBA center [[John Amaechi]], Hardaway replied: \u2018First of all, I wouldn't want him on my team.\u2019\n\nHardaway continued, \u2018You know, I hate gay people, so I let it be known,\u2019 Hardaway said. \u2018I don't like gay people and I don't like to be around gay people. I am homophobic. I don't like it. It shouldn't be in the world or in the United States.\u2019\n\nNBA commissioner David Stern, upon learning of the remarks Wednesday, banished Hardaway from All-Star weekend in Las Vegas.\u201d<ref name=\"Hardaway\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2766213 |title=Retired NBA star Hardaway says he hates 'gay people' |last1= |first1= |date=16 February 2007 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=12 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the comments, Hardaway apologized and attended counseling.  He has also made public appearances supporting [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]], including one in [[El Paso, Texas]] in response to an attempted recall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/dave_zirin/08/22/tim.hardaway/index.html |title=Hardaway makes up for comments, stands up for gay rights |last1=Zirin |first1=David |date=22 August 2011 |work=[[SI.com]] |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== David Samson\u2019s criticism of Ichiro Suzuki\u2019s contract ===\nOn July 11, 2007, [[Florida Marlins]] team president [[David Samson (baseball)|David Samson]] was featured on the show as he often is. When told by Dan about the report of [[Seattle Mariners]] player [[Ichiro Suzuki]] signing a 5-year, $100 million contract, Samson was in a state of disbelief. He went on to say that no player in baseball was worthy of that amount and that this deal would surely return the league to the days of ridiculous contracts, surely ruining the sport.\n\nThe next day, [[Bob Ryan]] of the ''Boston Globe'' appeared on the show to share opinion on the matter. He began by asking if Samson had just entered baseball yesterday. He then went on to criticize both Samson and the Florida Marlins franchise, while calling the deal as one of a well-managed franchise.<ref name=\"Samson\">''790 the Ticket''  [http://www.790theticket.com/audio/1267492097David%20Samson%20Show-%207-11-07.mp3 David Samson's interview on July 11th] Updated 2007-07-11, retrieved 2007-07-12</ref><ref name=\"Bob Ryan\">''790 the Ticket'' [http://www.790theticket.com/audio/1260416199Bob%20Ryan%20Interview-%207-12-07.mp3 Bob Ryan's response to Samson's remarks] Updated 2007-07-12, retrieved 2007-07-12</ref>\n\n=== Jay Bilas racial questions ===\n[[ESPN]] college basketball analyst [[Jay Bilas]] was on the show on April 7, 2008 to discuss NBA Draft prospects. When Le Batard asked if race was a factor in drafting, specifically if [[Michael Beasley]] would be drafted as highly if he had the same numbers but were white (the discussion originated with [[Tyler Hansbrough]]'s low draft projection despite his numbers). Bilas responded \u201cthis is stupid,\u201d and proceeded to end the interview.<ref name=\"Bilas\">''790 the Ticket'' [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CIGpfCxaz6c Jay Bilas talks NBA Draft with Le Batard 04/07/2008]</ref>\n\n=== Michael Phelps incident ===\n[[Michael Phelps]] appeared on the show shortly after the [[Beijing Olympics 2008|2008 Beijing Olympics]]. After not liking Le Batard's line of questioning, Phelps abruptly ended the interview however did not properly hang up the phone. Phelps could then be heard in the background calling Dan a \"joke\".<ref name=\"Phelps\">''790 the Ticket'' [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x6vqn7_lebatard-phelps_shortfilms Dan Le Batard interviews Michael Phelps 09/25/2008]</ref>\n\n=== Magic Johnson Controversy ===\nIn Feb, 2017, [[Magic Johnson]] was named as the President of Basketball operations of the [[Los Angeles Lakers]].  Le Batard then questioned his qualifications and cited less than successful ventures into both NBA coaching, and NBA broadcasting as well as his television show [[The Magic Hour (talk show)|The Magic Hour]] as evidence that giving Magic Johnson a position in which he apparently lacked experience was a questionable decision.  Of particular note, Le Batard stated that Magic Johnson's main qualification for this job was his ability to be charming and charismatic as well as his fame.  Le Batard made the following comment:\n\n\"What you\u2019ve got here though, is a testament to the power of fame. And a testament to the power of a modicum of charm. Because Magic Johnson is charming. But, Magic Johnson was given a late night television show, because he\u2019s famous and charming. Failed in 11 shows. Magic Johnson was given a head coaching job of the Lakers, because he\u2019s famous and charming, failed in 16 games. Magic Johnson, not interesting as a broadcaster, given broadcasting opportunity after broadcasting opportunity, because he\u2019s famous and charming. And now, he gets to run the entire Lakers organization because he\u2019s famous and charming. That\u2019s amazing. That\u2019s amazing. He\u2019s a very kind man, to be in his presence is to be awash in all the things people like about celebrity, he will make you feel special, but he wasn\u2019t good at any of those jobs I just mentioned, and he got all of those jobs, bypassing a whole lot of people who are more qualified, because he\u2019s famous and charming.\"\n\nOther ESPN commentators took offense to Le Batard's accusations that Magic Johnson was unqualified and also suggested that race played a part in Le Batard's accusations. [[Keyshawn Johnson]], was asked by [[Jorge Sedano]] \"If you are insinuating that Dan is, like, being prejudiced here...\" and Keyshawn Johnson responded \"That's what I'm insinuating\".  Sedano defended Le Batard, saying \"Well then you are 100% wrong.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/espn-espn-keyshawn-insinuates-le-batard-magic-jab-racist-article-1.2981194|title=ESPN vs. ESPN: Keyshawn insinuates Le Batard's Magic jab racist|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2017-06-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[LZ Granderson]] also hinted that race played a role in Le Batard's comments, stating that Le Batard implied through his comments about Magic Johnson's charisma that Magic Johnson had gotten the job through \"shucking and jiving\". [[Michael Wilbon]] also criticized Le Batard's comments on Twitter, though Wilbon's criticism abstained from any discussion of race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://larrybrownsports.com/media/michael-wilbon-dan-le-batard-magic-johnson-criticism/352954|title=Michael Wilbon goes after Dan Le Batard over Magic Johnson criticism|date=2017-02-23|work=Larry Brown Sports|access-date=2017-06-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Twitter beef with Michael Rapaport ===\nStemming from the Magic Johnson controversy, actor [[Michael Rapaport]], took to [[Twitter]] to call out Le Batard for his comments on Johnson, insinuating a Twitter beef between him and the show's crew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://slicemiami.com/2017/02/25/michael-rapaport-le-batard-twitter-mike-ryan/|title=\"Actor\" Michael Rapaport goes after Le Batard family on Twitter, gets eviscerated|last=Baumgard|first=Josh|date=2017-02-25|website=Slice Miami|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref> On February 24, 2017 Rapaport tweeted out, \"Dan Lebatard askin why Magic is runnin the Lakers & the rest of the world is asking why his Father is on TV show everyday. Who's qualified!?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MichaelRapaport/status/835290722295300100?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/dan-le-batard-michael-rapaport-espn-feud-magic-johnson-mike-ryan-ruiz-roy-bellamy-jon-weiner-stugotz-highly-questionable/1ku3yl1t1gisv1wq5gb076clks|title=Dan Lebatard askin why Magic is runnin the Lakers & the rest of the world is asking why his Father is on TV show everyday. Who's qualified!?|last=MichaelRapaport|date=2017-02-24|website=@MichaelRapaport|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref> Le Batard, responded to Rapaport by tweeting, \"The idea of my father feuding with Michael Rapaport is delightful and why I got into journalism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LeBatardShow/status/835308969707122688?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/dan-le-batard-michael-rapaport-espn-feud-magic-johnson-mike-ryan-ruiz-roy-bellamy-jon-weiner-stugotz-highly-questionable/1ku3yl1t1gisv1wq5gb076clks|title=The idea of my father feuding with Michael Rapaport is delightful and why I got into journalism.https://twitter.com/michaelrapaport/status/835290722295300100 \u2026|last=Show|first=Dan Le Batard|date=2017-02-24|website=@LeBatardShow|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\nThe situation escalated over the weekend as executive producer, Mike Ryan, then jumped in to defend Le Batard where he buried Rapaport, pointing out the actor's many forgettable roles in his movies. After a lengthy back and forth, Rapaport still insisted on attacking Ryan, and eventually, another of the show's producers, Roy Bellamy, jumped into the discussion. The Twitter beef reached its climax with Rapaport posting a racist photo of Bellamy and resulting in Ryan and Bellamy finishing their war with Rapaport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MichaelRyanRuiz/status/835615300162838529?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http://thebiglead.com/2017/03/02/the-michael-rapaportdan-le-batard-show-feud-has-gotten-very-personal/|title=.@roybelly Don't waste anymore time with ignorant @MichaelRapaport. Take a hint from his ex-wife and leave his ass for a woman.|last=Ryan|first=Mike|date=2017-02-25|website=@MichaelRyanRuiz|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref> Following the weekend, Le Batard briefly discussed the events that had occurred over the weekend on his show, and proclaimed the end of Rapaport's guest appearances at [[ESPN]]. Le Batard stated, \"These things are all about value. How much value do you have to the company? Not enough to be putting up racist stuff on Twitter. He doesn\u2019t work for the company. He\u2019s on The Jump every once in awhile. So I\u2019m guessing this is gonna cause him a problem. He doesn\u2019t have enough value to the company, I don\u2019t think, to withstand something like this.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thebiglead.com/2017/03/02/the-michael-rapaportdan-le-batard-show-feud-has-gotten-very-personal/|title=The Michael Rapaport/Dan Le Batard Show Feud Has Gotten Very Personal|date=2017-03-02|website=The Big Lead|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2017, Rapaport released an edition of his podcast, ''I Am Rapaport'', in which he fired back at the show once again, repeatedly insulting Le Batard and co-host Stugotz. Rapaport also threatened them with a defamation lawsuit for accusations that had been made about him having herpes stating, \u201cYou\u2019re claiming that I\u2019m not going work at ESPN? Let me tell you something. If I'm going down, the whole s\u2014 is burning down. If I'm going down, we\u2019re talking about defamation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/dan-le-batard-michael-rapaport-espn-feud-magic-johnson-mike-ryan-ruiz-roy-bellamy-jon-weiner-stugotz-highly-questionable/1ku3yl1t1gisv1wq5gb076clks|title=Dan Le Batard-Michael Rapaport ESPN media war 'for the ages' gets down, dirty|date=2017-03-03|work=Sporting News|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\nOn the May 5, 2017, episode of ''The Bill Simmons Podcast'', hosted by [[Bill Simmons]], a long time friend of Le Batard, Rapaport once again brought up the beef between him and the show. He repeatedly insulted Le Batard, Stugotz, and the show's producers saying they were only there to get his coffee. Simmons was uncomfortable for the entirety of Rapaport's rant against the show saying, \u201cI still feel awkward because I like all those guys. I wish this would work out.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://slicemiami.com/2017/05/06/michael-rapaport-le-batard-bill-simmons-podcast/|title=Cockroach Michael Rapaport attempts to reignite Le Batard beef on Bill Simmons Podcast|last=Baumgard|first=Josh|date=2017-05-06|website=Slice Miami|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Diamond Dallas Page incident ===\nOn April 4, 2017, professional wrestler [[Diamond Dallas Page]] appeared on the show following his induction in the Professional Wrestling Hall of Fame.  The interview appeared to be going well, until a question regarding a non-[[kayfabe]] feud with [[Scott Steiner]] was asked, specifically, a question about eye-gouging.  Page called Le Batard a \"monkey\" and went on a profanity-laced rant directed at Le Batard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/sports/2017/04/diamond-dallas-page-flips-out-curses-at-dan-le-batard-during-live-espn-interview|title=Diamond Dallas Page Flips Out and Curses at Dan Le Batard During Live ESPN Interview|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160828025913/http://www.theticketmiami.com/dan-lebatard/ Official website for the show on WAXY \"790 The Ticket\"]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dan Le Batard Show with Stugotz}}\n[[Category:American sports radio programs]]\n[[Category:ESPN Radio shows]]\n[[Category:Simulcasts]]\n[[Category:Television series based on radio programs]]\n[[Category:Fusion TV original programming]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox Radio Show\n| show_name       = The Dan Le Batard Show with Stugotz\n| image           = File:Dan Le Batard Show logo.png\n| imagesize       =\n| caption         =\n| other_names     =\n| format          = [[Sports]] [[Talk show|talk]]\n| runtime         = 4 hours\n| country         = [[United States]]\n| language        = [[English language|English]]\n| home_station    = [[WAXY (AM)|WAXY]] (2004 \u2013 August 2nd, 2019, August 5th, 2019 (local hour))<br>[[WQAM]] (August 5th, 2019\u2013present)<br>[[ESPN Radio]] (2013\u2013present)\n| television      = [[Fusion TV]] (2015\u20132016)<br>[[ESPNU]] (2015\u20132018)<br>[[ESPNEWS]] (2018\u2013present)\n| presenter       =\n| starring        = [[Dan Le Batard]] <br> [[Jon \"Stugotz\" Weiner]]\n| announcer       = Gonzalo \"Papi\" Le Batard\n| creator         =\n| writer          =\n| director        =\n| producer        = Mike Ryan Ruiz, Roy Bellamy, Billy \"Guillermo\" Gil, Chris \"I'm Chris Cote ESPN\" Cote, Allyson Turner\n| executive_producer = \n| narrated        =\n| record_location = [[Miami Beach]], [[Florida]]\n| first_aired     = September 1, 2004\n| last_aired      = present\n| num_series      =\n| num_episodes    =\n| audio_format    =\n| opentheme       = A mashup mix featuring the ''[[Blade (film)|Blade]]'' theme, [[Brooklyn Bounce]]'s \"This is the Real Bass,\" and [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]]'s \"[[Party Up (Up in Here)]],\" featuring clips offering signature moments from the show's various personalities.\n| endtheme        = Gonzalo Le Batard saying, \"We will talk to you ma\u00f1ana, this has been the Dan Le Batard Show on ESPN Radio\" and [[Gregg Popovich]] saying \"We live in a racist country.\"\n| website         = [http://espn.go.com/espnradio/show?showId=danlebatard The Dan Le Batard Show on ESPN Radio]<br />[http://www.theticketmiami.com/dan-lebatard/ www.theticketmiami.com]\n| podcast         = [http://lebatard.790theticket.libsynpro.com/rss Podcast RSS]<br />[http://espn.go.com/espnradio/podcast/archive?id=9941853 Podcast on ESPN Radio]}}\n\n'''''The Dan Le Batard Show with Stugotz''''' is a [[sports radio|sports]] [[talk radio]] show hosted by [[Dan Le Batard]] and [[Jon \"Stugotz\" Weiner]] and broadcast on [[WQAM|WQAM \u201c560 The Joe\u201d]] in South Florida and [[ESPN Radio]] affiliates nationwide. The show was heard locally Monday through Friday from 9 AM to 1 PM ET on [[WAXY (AM)|WAXY]] AM 790 \"The Ticket\" until August 5th, 2019. It is now heard locally and nationally on ESPN Radio and [[ESPNEWS]] from 10 AM to 1 PM (prior to April 2, 2018, the television simulcast was aired on [[ESPNU]]).  The show features commentary on the day's sports news, perspective on other news stories, interviews with sports analysts and sports figures, as well as a generous blend of pop culture and listener interaction.  The hosts are known for their self-deprecating humor, which carries over onto the show through running jokes. Le Batard and Stugotz interact throughout the show with executive producer Mike Ryan, show booker Allyson Turner, and fellow producers Roy Bellamy, Billy \"Guillermo\" Gil, and Chris \"Fats and Info\" Cote, collectively nicknamed the Shipping Container Filled with Frightened Refugees. The show commonly refers to themselves as a \"marching band to nowhere<nowiki>''</nowiki> and a <nowiki>''</nowiki>flying saucer of BS<nowiki>''</nowiki> \n\nCurrently, Le Batard and Stugotz are joined on-air by Greg Cote of [[The Miami Herald]] on Tuesdays, and additional ESPN personalities (including [[Sarah Spain]], [[Domonique Foxworth]], [[Mina Kimes]] and others) make regular guest hosting appearances.\n\nAfter running for nine years on local radio, The Dan Le Batard Show debuted on ESPN Radio on September 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dan Le Batard launches ESPN Radio show Monday |url=http://www.awfulannouncing.com/2013/september/dan-le-batard-launches-espn-radio-show-monday.html |author=Matt Yoder |work=Awful Announcing |publisher=Bloguin |date=27 September 2013 |accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, It was announced that the show would be televised on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]] starting May 19, 2015.<ref>http://wearefusion.tumblr.com/post/111576430949/espns-dan-le-batard-to-bring-his-signature-voice</ref> After the departure of [[Colin Cowherd]] from ESPN, the network moved the time slot of the show into the 10 AM to 1 PM slot formerly occupied by [[The Herd with Colin Cowherd]], and moved the live simulcast to [[ESPNU]], with the Fusion broadcast shifting to tape delay from 1 to 4 PM. On May 18, 2016, Fusion aired the show for the last time as the year-long contract with ABC/Disney was expired and was not renewed. The TV portion of the show then remained solely on ESPNU afterwards with the show airing live from 10 AM to 1 PM with no outlet for a tape-delay. On January 10, 2017, the final hour of the show began simulcasting on [[ESPN2]], but in July 2017, the show's final hour returned to airing on ESPNU. On April 2, 2018, the show's simulcast moved to [[ESPNEWS]].\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Tim Hardaway's homophobic comments ===\nOn February 14, 2007, the week of the [[2007 NBA All-Star Game]], former [[Miami Heat]] player [[Tim Hardaway]] appeared on the show.  When asked if he would be accepting of a gay teammate, such as retired NBA center [[John Amaechi]], Hardaway replied: \u2018First of all, I wouldn't want him on my team.\u2019\n\nHardaway continued, \u2018You know, I hate gay people, so I let it be known,\u2019 Hardaway said. \u2018I don't like gay people and I don't like to be around gay people. I am homophobic. I don't like it. It shouldn't be in the world or in the United States.\u2019\n\nNBA commissioner David Stern, upon learning of the remarks Wednesday, banished Hardaway from All-Star weekend in Las Vegas.\u201d<ref name=\"Hardaway\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2766213 |title=Retired NBA star Hardaway says he hates 'gay people' |last1= |first1= |date=16 February 2007 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=12 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the comments, Hardaway apologized and attended counseling.  He has also made public appearances supporting [[LGBT rights in the United States|gay rights]], including one in [[El Paso, Texas]] in response to an attempted recall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/dave_zirin/08/22/tim.hardaway/index.html |title=Hardaway makes up for comments, stands up for gay rights |last1=Zirin |first1=David |date=22 August 2011 |work=[[SI.com]] |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== David Samson\u2019s criticism of Ichiro Suzuki\u2019s contract ===\nOn July 11, 2007, [[Florida Marlins]] team president [[David Samson (baseball)|David Samson]] was featured on the show as he often is. When told by Dan about the report of [[Seattle Mariners]] player [[Ichiro Suzuki]] signing a 5-year, $100 million contract, Samson was in a state of disbelief. He went on to say that no player in baseball was worthy of that amount and that this deal would surely return the league to the days of ridiculous contracts, surely ruining the sport.\n\nThe next day, [[Bob Ryan]] of the ''Boston Globe'' appeared on the show to share opinion on the matter. He began by asking if Samson had just entered baseball yesterday. He then went on to criticize both Samson and the Florida Marlins franchise, while calling the deal as one of a well-managed franchise.<ref name=\"Samson\">''790 the Ticket''  [http://www.790theticket.com/audio/1267492097David%20Samson%20Show-%207-11-07.mp3 David Samson's interview on July 11th] Updated 2007-07-11, retrieved 2007-07-12</ref><ref name=\"Bob Ryan\">''790 the Ticket'' [http://www.790theticket.com/audio/1260416199Bob%20Ryan%20Interview-%207-12-07.mp3 Bob Ryan's response to Samson's remarks] Updated 2007-07-12, retrieved 2007-07-12</ref>\n\n=== Jay Bilas racial questions ===\n[[ESPN]] college basketball analyst [[Jay Bilas]] was on the show on April 7, 2008 to discuss NBA Draft prospects. When Le Batard asked if race was a factor in drafting, specifically if [[Michael Beasley]] would be drafted as highly if he had the same numbers but were white (the discussion originated with [[Tyler Hansbrough]]'s low draft projection despite his numbers). Bilas responded \u201cthis is stupid,\u201d and proceeded to end the interview.<ref name=\"Bilas\">''790 the Ticket'' [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CIGpfCxaz6c Jay Bilas talks NBA Draft with Le Batard 04/07/2008]</ref>\n\n=== Michael Phelps incident ===\n[[Michael Phelps]] appeared on the show shortly after the [[Beijing Olympics 2008|2008 Beijing Olympics]]. After not liking Le Batard's line of questioning, Phelps abruptly ended the interview however did not properly hang up the phone. Phelps could then be heard in the background calling Dan a \"joke\".<ref name=\"Phelps\">''790 the Ticket'' [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x6vqn7_lebatard-phelps_shortfilms Dan Le Batard interviews Michael Phelps 09/25/2008]</ref>\n\n=== Magic Johnson Controversy ===\nIn Feb, 2017, [[Magic Johnson]] was named as the President of Basketball operations of the [[Los Angeles Lakers]].  Le Batard then questioned his qualifications and cited less than successful ventures into both NBA coaching, and NBA broadcasting as well as his television show [[The Magic Hour (talk show)|The Magic Hour]] as evidence that giving Magic Johnson a position in which he apparently lacked experience was a questionable decision.  Of particular note, Le Batard stated that Magic Johnson's main qualification for this job was his ability to be charming and charismatic as well as his fame.  Le Batard made the following comment:\n\n\"What you\u2019ve got here though, is a testament to the power of fame. And a testament to the power of a modicum of charm. Because Magic Johnson is charming. But, Magic Johnson was given a late night television show, because he\u2019s famous and charming. Failed in 11 shows. Magic Johnson was given a head coaching job of the Lakers, because he\u2019s famous and charming, failed in 16 games. Magic Johnson, not interesting as a broadcaster, given broadcasting opportunity after broadcasting opportunity, because he\u2019s famous and charming. And now, he gets to run the entire Lakers organization because he\u2019s famous and charming. That\u2019s amazing. That\u2019s amazing. He\u2019s a very kind man, to be in his presence is to be awash in all the things people like about celebrity, he will make you feel special, but he wasn\u2019t good at any of those jobs I just mentioned, and he got all of those jobs, bypassing a whole lot of people who are more qualified, because he\u2019s famous and charming.\"\n\nOther ESPN commentators took offense to Le Batard's accusations that Magic Johnson was unqualified and also suggested that race played a part in Le Batard's accusations. [[Keyshawn Johnson]], was asked by [[Jorge Sedano]] \"If you are insinuating that Dan is, like, being prejudiced here...\" and Keyshawn Johnson responded \"That's what I'm insinuating\".  Sedano defended Le Batard, saying \"Well then you are 100% wrong.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/espn-espn-keyshawn-insinuates-le-batard-magic-jab-racist-article-1.2981194|title=ESPN vs. ESPN: Keyshawn insinuates Le Batard's Magic jab racist|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2017-06-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[LZ Granderson]] also hinted that race played a role in Le Batard's comments, stating that Le Batard implied through his comments about Magic Johnson's charisma that Magic Johnson had gotten the job through \"shucking and jiving\". [[Michael Wilbon]] also criticized Le Batard's comments on Twitter, though Wilbon's criticism abstained from any discussion of race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://larrybrownsports.com/media/michael-wilbon-dan-le-batard-magic-johnson-criticism/352954|title=Michael Wilbon goes after Dan Le Batard over Magic Johnson criticism|date=2017-02-23|work=Larry Brown Sports|access-date=2017-06-08|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Twitter beef with Michael Rapaport ===\nStemming from the Magic Johnson controversy, actor [[Michael Rapaport]], took to [[Twitter]] to call out Le Batard for his comments on Johnson, insinuating a Twitter beef between him and the show's crew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://slicemiami.com/2017/02/25/michael-rapaport-le-batard-twitter-mike-ryan/|title=\"Actor\" Michael Rapaport goes after Le Batard family on Twitter, gets eviscerated|last=Baumgard|first=Josh|date=2017-02-25|website=Slice Miami|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref> On February 24, 2017 Rapaport tweeted out, \"Dan Lebatard askin why Magic is runnin the Lakers & the rest of the world is asking why his Father is on TV show everyday. Who's qualified!?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MichaelRapaport/status/835290722295300100?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/dan-le-batard-michael-rapaport-espn-feud-magic-johnson-mike-ryan-ruiz-roy-bellamy-jon-weiner-stugotz-highly-questionable/1ku3yl1t1gisv1wq5gb076clks|title=Dan Lebatard askin why Magic is runnin the Lakers & the rest of the world is asking why his Father is on TV show everyday. Who's qualified!?|last=MichaelRapaport|date=2017-02-24|website=@MichaelRapaport|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref> Le Batard, responded to Rapaport by tweeting, \"The idea of my father feuding with Michael Rapaport is delightful and why I got into journalism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LeBatardShow/status/835308969707122688?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/dan-le-batard-michael-rapaport-espn-feud-magic-johnson-mike-ryan-ruiz-roy-bellamy-jon-weiner-stugotz-highly-questionable/1ku3yl1t1gisv1wq5gb076clks|title=The idea of my father feuding with Michael Rapaport is delightful and why I got into journalism.https://twitter.com/michaelrapaport/status/835290722295300100 \u2026|last=Show|first=Dan Le Batard|date=2017-02-24|website=@LeBatardShow|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\nThe situation escalated over the weekend as executive producer, Mike Ryan, then jumped in to defend Le Batard where he buried Rapaport, pointing out the actor's many forgettable roles in his movies. After a lengthy back and forth, Rapaport still insisted on attacking Ryan, and eventually, another of the show's producers, Roy Bellamy, jumped into the discussion. The Twitter beef reached its climax with Rapaport posting a racist photo of Bellamy and resulting in Ryan and Bellamy finishing their war with Rapaport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MichaelRyanRuiz/status/835615300162838529?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http://thebiglead.com/2017/03/02/the-michael-rapaportdan-le-batard-show-feud-has-gotten-very-personal/|title=.@roybelly Don't waste anymore time with ignorant @MichaelRapaport. Take a hint from his ex-wife and leave his ass for a woman.|last=Ryan|first=Mike|date=2017-02-25|website=@MichaelRyanRuiz|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref> Following the weekend, Le Batard briefly discussed the events that had occurred over the weekend on his show, and proclaimed the end of Rapaport's guest appearances at [[ESPN]]. Le Batard stated, \"These things are all about value. How much value do you have to the company? Not enough to be putting up racist stuff on Twitter. He doesn\u2019t work for the company. He\u2019s on The Jump every once in awhile. So I\u2019m guessing this is gonna cause him a problem. He doesn\u2019t have enough value to the company, I don\u2019t think, to withstand something like this.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thebiglead.com/2017/03/02/the-michael-rapaportdan-le-batard-show-feud-has-gotten-very-personal/|title=The Michael Rapaport/Dan Le Batard Show Feud Has Gotten Very Personal|date=2017-03-02|website=The Big Lead|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2017, Rapaport released an edition of his podcast, ''I Am Rapaport'', in which he fired back at the show once again, repeatedly insulting Le Batard and co-host Stugotz. Rapaport also threatened them with a defamation lawsuit for accusations that had been made about him having herpes stating, \u201cYou\u2019re claiming that I\u2019m not going work at ESPN? Let me tell you something. If I'm going down, the whole s\u2014 is burning down. If I'm going down, we\u2019re talking about defamation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/dan-le-batard-michael-rapaport-espn-feud-magic-johnson-mike-ryan-ruiz-roy-bellamy-jon-weiner-stugotz-highly-questionable/1ku3yl1t1gisv1wq5gb076clks|title=Dan Le Batard-Michael Rapaport ESPN media war 'for the ages' gets down, dirty|date=2017-03-03|work=Sporting News|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\nOn the May 5, 2017, episode of ''The Bill Simmons Podcast'', hosted by [[Bill Simmons]], a long time friend of Le Batard, Rapaport once again brought up the beef between him and the show. He repeatedly insulted Le Batard, Stugotz, and the show's producers saying they were only there to get his coffee. Simmons was uncomfortable for the entirety of Rapaport's rant against the show saying, \u201cI still feel awkward because I like all those guys. I wish this would work out.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://slicemiami.com/2017/05/06/michael-rapaport-le-batard-bill-simmons-podcast/|title=Cockroach Michael Rapaport attempts to reignite Le Batard beef on Bill Simmons Podcast|last=Baumgard|first=Josh|date=2017-05-06|website=Slice Miami|access-date=2017-06-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Diamond Dallas Page incident ===\nOn April 4, 2017, professional wrestler [[Diamond Dallas Page]] appeared on the show following his induction in the Professional Wrestling Hall of Fame.  The interview appeared to be going well, until a question regarding a non-[[kayfabe]] feud with [[Scott Steiner]] was asked, specifically, a question about eye-gouging.  Page called Le Batard a \"monkey\" and went on a profanity-laced rant directed at Le Batard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/sports/2017/04/diamond-dallas-page-flips-out-curses-at-dan-le-batard-during-live-espn-interview|title=Diamond Dallas Page Flips Out and Curses at Dan Le Batard During Live ESPN Interview|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160828025913/http://www.theticketmiami.com/dan-lebatard/ Official website for the show on WAXY \"790 The Ticket\"]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dan Le Batard Show with Stugotz}}\n[[Category:American sports radio programs]]\n[[Category:ESPN Radio shows]]\n[[Category:Simulcasts]]\n[[Category:Television series based on radio programs]]\n[[Category:Fusion TV original programming]]\n", "name_user": "99.113.181.210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Add show content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dan_Le_Batard_Show_with_Stugotz"}
{"title_page": "War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire", "text_new": "{{italictitle}}\n'''''War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire''''' is a 1935 non-fiction book by Tatsuji Takeuchi, published by [[Doubleday, Doran, and Company]].\n\nWilliam L. Langer of ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' described it as \"a scholarly and thoroughly documented analysis of the Japanese constitutional system and of the technique of Japanese diplomacy.\"<ref name=Langer>{{cite web|author=Langer, William L.|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/1936-04-01/war-and-diplomacy-japanese-empire|title=War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[Foreign Affairs]]|date=1936-04-01|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThomas Harrington in ''[[International Affairs (journal)|International Affairs]]'' stated that \"a special study of the internal operations of the Government and of the motives and traditions which influence its activities.\"<ref>Harrington, p. 788.</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn 1927 the Social Science Research Council at the [[University of Chicago]] started a series about why wars are started, and this book became a part of the series.<ref name=Steigerp788>Steiger, p. 788.</ref>\n\nThe author taught international relations at [[Kwansei Gakuin University]]. He wrote the body of his work in the [[University of Chicago]],<ref name=Spectator>{{cite web|author=Hudson, G|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/1st-may-1936/23/japan-and-the-world-war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japan|title=Japan and the World War and Diplomacy in the Japanese|work=[[Spectator]]|date=1936-05-01|volume=156|issue=5627|page=799|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref> The author had access to multiple Japanese sources not yet available in the West,<ref name=Langer/> an the majority of the sources were Japanese.<ref name=Quigleyp472>Quigley, p. 472.</ref> Quigley stated that the [[Japanese Diet]]<!--Stated in-source as \"House of Representatives\"--> had relatively little influence on foreign relations but the ability to get sources about that aspect meant it had more emphasis in the book.<ref name=Quigleyp473>Quigley, p. 473.</ref>\n\nMost of the book was written in 1931, but publication was delayed after the [[Mukden Incident]]. The author wrote his preface at Kwansei Gakuin on June 20, 1935.<ref name=Spectator/>\n\n==Content==\nThe book covers the period up to 1933. The author did not intend to create a complete history of international relations between Japan and other countries. According to Takeuchi, \"the substance of policy\" is not the focus of the book, and instead \"procedure\" is the focus.<ref name=Spectator/> Quigley stated that nevertheless the book contains valuable information regarding the former.<ref name=Quigleyp472/>\n\nPart I discusses the structure of Japanese government agencies that engage in foreign relations;<ref name=Steigerp789>Steiger, 789.</ref> it has 780 pages.<ref name=Noremp280>Norem, p. 280.</ref> Part II includes eighteen case studies,<ref name=Steigerp789>Steiger, 789.</ref> each about a different diplomatic event,<ref name=Quigleyp472/> and discusses Japan's foreign affairs, including its end of participation in the [[League of Nations]].<ref name=Steigerp789/> Harold S. Quigley in ''[[Pacific Affairs (journal)|Pacific Affairs]]'' described it as the \"main\" section of the book,<ref name=Quigleyp472/> and Ralph A. Norem of the [[University of California Los Angeles]] described it as \"the main body of the book\".<ref name=Noremp280/> Part III contains three chapters and includes Takeuchi's views of the foreign affairs processes by the Japanese government,<ref name=Steigerp789/> based upon the content of Part II.<ref name=Noremp280/>\n\nThere is an appendix, a bibliography, and an index. The first one includes a copy of the [[Japanese constitution]]. The book contains footnotes, described by Quigley as \"extensive\", and which include information on Japanese government policy.<ref name=Quigleyp472/>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Spectator]]'' stated that while Japan had not reached a \"totalitarian\" environment yet, in light of the increasing militarization, \"it seems strange that so independent a mind should be tolerated at all.\"<ref name=Spectator/> It argued in regards to the content about the [[invasion of Manchuria]] that it is \"a most valuable account\".<ref name=Spectator/>\n\nLanger praised the sourcing and described it as \"One of the most important books of the quarter.\"<ref name=Langer/>\n\nQuigley wrote that stated \"the work as a whole is entitled to the grateful attention of all students of international relations.\"<ref name=Quigleyp473/> Quigley added that \"One feels that what is written is sincerely written.\"<ref name=Quigleyp473/>\n\nG. Nye Steiger of [[Simmons College]] wrote that the author \"succeeded in throwing a flood of much needed light\" on the subject matter.<ref name=Steigerp788/>\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal |last=Harrington  |first= Thomas|date=September-October 1936 |title= War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[International Affairs (journal)|International Affairs]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place= |volume=15|issue=5|pages=788-790 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2602462?seq=1 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |jstor=2602462}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Norem |first=Ralph A.|title=War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire (Book Review)|work=[[Pacific Historical Review]]|date=1936-09-01|volume=5|issue=3|page=280-281|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3634031|jstor=3634031}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Quigley |first= Harold |date=1936-09-01|title= War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work = [[Pacific Affairs]] |volume=9|issue=3|page=471|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2750670|jstor=2750670}} \n* {{cite journal |last= Steiger|first=G. Nye |date=August 1936 |title= War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[American Political Science Review]] |publisher= [[Cambridge University Press]]|publication-place= |volume=30|issue=4|page=788-790 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/american-political-science-review/article/war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japanese-empire-by-tatsuji-takeuchi-introduction-by-quincy-wright-garden-city-doubleday-doran-and-company-1935-pp-xix-505-when-japan-goes-to-war-by-o-tanin-and-e-yohan-new-york-the-vanguard-press-1936-pp-271-togo-and-the-rise-of-japanese-sea-power-by-edwin-a-falk-with-a-foreword-by-rear-admiral-bradley-a-fiske-new-york-longmans-green-and-co1936-pp-xiii-508/5E8BF4737A58097DDF9EA5082B92AB50 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.2307/1947966}} - Published online on 2 September 2013.\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.6461 War And Diplomacy In The Japanese Empire]'' - [[Internet Archive]]\n* ''[https://www.questia.com/library/77350247/war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japanese-empire War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire]'' in [[Questia]]\n[[Category:1935 books]]\n{{book-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italictitle}}\n'''''War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire''''' is a 1935 non-fiction book by Tatsuji Takeuchi, published by [[Doubleday, Doran, and Company]].\n\nWilliam L. Langer of ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' described it as \"a scholarly and thoroughly documented analysis of the Japanese constitutional system and of the technique of Japanese diplomacy.\"<ref name=Langer>{{cite web|author=Langer, William L.|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/1936-04-01/war-and-diplomacy-japanese-empire|title=War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[Foreign Affairs]]|date=1936-04-01|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThomas Harrington in ''[[International Affairs (journal)|International Affairs]]'' stated that \"a special study of the internal operations of the Government and of the motives and traditions which influence its activities.\"<ref>Harrington, p. 788.</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn 1927 the Social Science Research Council at the [[University of Chicago]] started a series about why wars are started, and this book became a part of the series.<ref name=Steigerp788>Steiger, p. 788.</ref>\n\nThe author taught international relations at [[Kwansei Gakuin University]]. He wrote the body of his work in the [[University of Chicago]],<ref name=Spectator>{{cite web|author=Hudson, G|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/1st-may-1936/23/japan-and-the-world-war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japan|title=Japan and the World War and Diplomacy in the Japanese|work=[[Spectator]]|date=1936-05-01|volume=156|issue=5627|page=799|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref> The author had access to multiple Japanese sources not yet available in the West,<ref name=Langer/> an the majority of the sources were Japanese.<ref name=Quigleyp472>Quigley, p. 472.</ref> Quigley stated that the [[Japanese Diet]]<!--Stated in-source as \"House of Representatives\"--> had relatively little influence on foreign relations but the ability to get sources about that aspect meant it had more emphasis in the book.<ref name=Quigleyp473>Quigley, p. 473.</ref>\n\nMost of the book was written in 1931, but publication was delayed after the [[Mukden Incident]]. The author wrote his preface at Kwansei Gakuin on June 20, 1935.<ref name=Spectator/>\n\n==Content==\nThe book covers the period up to 1933. The author did not intend to create a complete history of international relations between Japan and other countries. According to Takeuchi, \"the substance of policy\" is not the focus of the book, and instead \"procedure\" is the focus.<ref name=Spectator/> Quigley stated that nevertheless the book contains valuable information regarding the former.<ref name=Quigleyp472/>\n\nPart I discusses the structure of Japanese government agencies that engage in foreign relations;<ref name=Steigerp789>Steiger, 789.</ref> it has 780 pages.<ref name=Noremp280/> Part II includes eighteen case studies,<ref name=Steigerp789>Steiger, 789.</ref> each about a different diplomatic event,<ref name=Quigleyp472/> and discusses Japan's foreign affairs, including its end of participation in the [[League of Nations]].<ref name=Steigerp789/> Harold S. Quigley in ''[[Pacific Affairs (journal)|Pacific Affairs]]'' described it as the \"main\" section of the book,<ref name=Quigleyp472/> and Ralph A. Norem of the [[University of California Los Angeles]] described it as \"the main body of the book\".<ref name=Noremp280/> Part III contains three chapters and includes Takeuchi's views of the foreign affairs processes by the Japanese government,<ref name=Steigerp789/> based upon the content of Part II.<ref name=Noremp280/>\n\nThere is an appendix, a bibliography, and an index. The first one includes a copy of the [[Japanese constitution]]. The book contains footnotes, described by Quigley as \"extensive\", and which include information on Japanese government policy.<ref name=Quigleyp472/>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Spectator]]'' stated that while Japan had not reached a \"totalitarian\" environment yet, in light of the increasing militarization, \"it seems strange that so independent a mind should be tolerated at all.\"<ref name=Spectator/> It argued in regards to the content about the [[invasion of Manchuria]] that it is \"a most valuable account\".<ref name=Spectator/>\n\nLanger praised the sourcing and described it as \"One of the most important books of the quarter.\"<ref name=Langer/>\n\nQuigley wrote that stated \"the work as a whole is entitled to the grateful attention of all students of international relations.\"<ref name=Quigleyp473/> Quigley added that \"One feels that what is written is sincerely written.\"<ref name=Quigleyp473/>\n\nG. Nye Steiger of [[Simmons College]] wrote that the author \"succeeded in throwing a flood of much needed light\" on the subject matter.<ref name=Steigerp788/>\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal |last=Harrington  |first= Thomas|date=September-October 1936 |title= War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[International Affairs (journal)|International Affairs]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place= |volume=15|issue=5|pages=788-790 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2602462?seq=1 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |jstor=2602462}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Norem |first=Ralph A.|title=War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire (Book Review)|work=[[Pacific Historical Review]]|date=1936-09-01|volume=5|issue=3|page=280-281|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3634031|jstor=3634031}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Quigley |first= Harold |date=1936-09-01|title= War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work = [[Pacific Affairs]] |volume=9|issue=3|page=471|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2750670|jstor=2750670}} \n* {{cite journal |last= Steiger|first=G. Nye |date=August 1936 |title= War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[American Political Science Review]] |publisher= [[Cambridge University Press]]|publication-place= |volume=30|issue=4|page=788-790 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/american-political-science-review/article/war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japanese-empire-by-tatsuji-takeuchi-introduction-by-quincy-wright-garden-city-doubleday-doran-and-company-1935-pp-xix-505-when-japan-goes-to-war-by-o-tanin-and-e-yohan-new-york-the-vanguard-press-1936-pp-271-togo-and-the-rise-of-japanese-sea-power-by-edwin-a-falk-with-a-foreword-by-rear-admiral-bradley-a-fiske-new-york-longmans-green-and-co1936-pp-xiii-508/5E8BF4737A58097DDF9EA5082B92AB50 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.2307/1947966}} - Published online on 2 September 2013.\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.6461 War And Diplomacy In The Japanese Empire]'' - [[Internet Archive]]\n* ''[https://www.questia.com/library/77350247/war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japanese-empire War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire]'' in [[Questia]]\n[[Category:1935 books]]\n{{book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WhisperToMe", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_and_Diplomacy_in_the_Japanese_Empire"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Teague (automotive designer)", "text_new": "{{For|the basketball player Jeff Teague|Jeff Teague (basketball)}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jeff Teague\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1956|10|3}}\n| birth_place = .\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2016|7|29|1956|10|3}}\n| death_place = [[Agoura Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Automotive design]]er \n}}\n\n'''Jeff Teague''' was an [[Americans|American]] [[automotive design]]er with automotive companies including [[Volkswagen]], [[Ford Motor Company]] and [[Mitsubishi Motors]]. \n\n== Background ==\nTeague was born to Marian Teague and renowned industrial designer, [[Richard A. Teague]], widely known for his design work with [[American Motors Corporation]], including such cars as the [[AMC Gremlin|Gremlin]], [[AMC AMX|AMX]], [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]] and [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]] and [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]].\n\nJeff Teague graduated from the [[Art Center College of Design]] in Pasadena California in 1978. Subsequently he as a designer and design consultant with Ford Motor Corporation in Dearborn Michigan, was a senior designer with [[Mitsubishi Motors North America]] in Cypress California, was Chief Designer Volkswagen AG of Germany in Wolfsburg, Germany, and Studio Chief for Volkswagen of America<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Celebrate the Life and Design of Jeff Teague\n |publisher    = Autodesigno\n |author       = \n |date         = August 2, 2016\n |url          = https://autodesigno.com/jeff-teague-a-celebration-of-life-and-design/}}</ref> He was subsequently the senior designer at [[Mitsubishi Motors]] of America in Simi Valley California, and later was design consultant with [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]] and [[Kia Motors|Kia]]. \n\n[[File:1984-1987 Lincoln Continental -- 09-03-2010.jpg|thumb|1984-87 Lincoln Continental]]\nWhile working at [[Ford Motor Company]], Teague designed the [[Ford Taurus]] and [[Mercury Sable]] wagon,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |last=Garrison |first=Jasper |title=Killing the Goose... Chapter 21: Taurus |date=2003 |publisher=Smart Fellows Press |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120205003020/http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |archivedate=5 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> and was the principal designer for the 1984 [[Lincoln Continental]].\n\nIn 1998, Teague started a design program in Automotive and Industrial design at the [[Academy of Art University]] (formerly Academy of Art College) in San Francisco. Teague hired and managed a multi-cultural international staff and developed the program curriculum and syllabus, later serving on the the Board of Directors until his death in 2016.\n\n== Career and design work ==\nTeague has provided design services and consulting services to [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]], [[Kia Motors|Kia]], [[Subaru]], and others. He now heads his own firm: Teague Design<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=105333 |publisher=Edmund's Inside Line |title=Duesenberg May Hit the Streets Again |archivedate=18 April 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050418223340/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId%3D105333 |accessdate=20 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He started the company in 1998 in [[Agoura Hills, California]], and it was incorporated in 2000.\n\nHe designed an updated ''AMX 4'' based on AMC's mid-engine sports car that contributed to his father's design reputation.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/AMX-4.html |publisher=Teague Design |title=AMX3 / AMX4 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120508225717/http://www.teaguedesigninc.com/AMX-4.html |archivedate=8 May 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2006, Teague was providing design services for the revival [[Duesenberg]] line of automobiles.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/jan2006/bw20060131_605519.htm |journal=Business Week |title=Duesenberg Rises Again |first=Reena |last=Jana |date=1 February 2006 |accessdate=19 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523144452/http://www.businessweek.com/autos/content/jan2006/bw20060131_605519.htm |archivedate=23 May 2012 }}</ref> The new design of the ''Duesenberg II Torpedo Coupe'' was delayed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2007/09/26/duesenberg-revival-delayed/ |title=Duesenberg revival delayed |first=Dan |last=Roth |date=26 September 2007 |accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> He is Chief Design Director for the new [[Baldwin, Wisconsin]], company and the car was expected to be introduced in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.duesenbergcustomcoach.com/torpedocoupe.html |title=Duesenberg Torpedo Coupe |publisher=Duesenberg Motors |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120107122102/http://duesenbergcustomcoach.com/torpedocoupe.html |archivedate=7 January 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> In 2012, the company bought a building in Baldwin to produce its replica cars on a modern Ford chassis, as well as a [[motorized tricycle]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.twincities.com/ci_19989661 |title=Duesenberg Motors' replica cars to be made in Baldwin, Wis. |first=Andy |last=Rathbun |publisher=Pioneer Press |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nJeff Teague died on July 29, 2016 at his home in [[Agoura Hills, California]], at age 59.<ref name=\"hemmings\">{{cite web|publisher=Hemmings Motor News |title=Designer Jeff Teague, Son of Dick Teague, dies at 59 |accessdate=2018-12-19 |url=https://www.hemmings.com/blog/2016/08/05/designer-jeff-teague-son-of-dick-teague-dies-at-59/ }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Jeff Teague interview by ASME: {{cite web|url= https://www.asme.org/engineering-topics/articles/automotive-design/car-designing-past-and-present |title= Car Designing: Past and Present |date=January 2012 |first=Eric |last=Butterman |publisher=American Society of Mechanical Engineers ASME |accessdate=20 April 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teague, Jeff}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:American automobile designers]]\n[[Category:American Motors people]]\n[[Category:Mitsubishi Motors people]]\n[[Category:Ford designers]]\n[[Category:People from Agoura Hills, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the basketball player Jeff Teague|Jeff Teague (basketball)}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Jeff Teague\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1956|10|3}}\n| birth_place = .\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2016|7|29|1956|10|3}}\n| death_place = [[Agoura Hills, California]], U.S.\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Automotive design]]er \n}}\n\n'''Jeff Teague''' was an [[Americans|American]] [[automotive design]]er with automotive companies including [[Volkswagen]], [[Ford Motor Company]] and [[Mitsubishi Motors]]. \n\n== Background ==\nTeague was born to Marian Teague and renowned industrial designer, [[Richard A. Teague]], widely known for his design work with [[American Motors Corporation]], including such cars as the [[AMC Gremlin|Gremlin]], [[AMC AMX|AMX]], [[AMC Hornet|Hornet]] and [[AMC Pacer|Pacer]] and [[Jeep Cherokee (XJ)]].\n\nJeff Teague graduated from the [[Art Center College of Design]] in Pasadena California in 1978. Subsequently he as a designer and design consultant with Ford Motor Corporation in Dearborn Michigan, was a senior designer with [[Mitsubishi Motors America]] in Cypress California, was Chief Designer Volkswagen AG of Germany in Wolfsburg, Germany, and Studio Chief for Volkswagen of America<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Celebrate the Life and Design of Jeff Teague\n |publisher    = Autodesigno\n |author       = \n |date         = August 2, 2016\n |url          = https://autodesigno.com/jeff-teague-a-celebration-of-life-and-design/}}</ref> He was subsequently the senior designer at [[Mitsubishi Motors]] of America in Simi Valley California, and later was design consultant with [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]] and [[Kia Motors|Kia]]. \n\n[[File:1984-1987 Lincoln Continental -- 09-03-2010.jpg|thumb|1984-87 Lincoln Continental]]\nWhile working at [[Ford Motor Company]], Teague designed the [[Ford Taurus]] and [[Mercury Sable]] wagon,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |last=Garrison |first=Jasper |title=Killing the Goose... Chapter 21: Taurus |date=2003 |publisher=Smart Fellows Press |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120205003020/http://www.smartfellowspress.com/killing_the_goose_21.htm |archivedate=5 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref> and was the principal designer for the 1984 [[Lincoln Continental]].\n\nIn 1998, Teague started a design program in Automotive and Industrial design at the [[Academy of Art University]] (formerly Academy of Art College) in San Francisco. Teague hired and managed a multi-cultural international staff and developed the program curriculum and syllabus, later serving on the the Board of Directors until his death in 2016.\n\n== Career and design work ==\nTeague has provided design services and consulting services to [[Hyundai Motor Group|Hyundai]], [[Kia Motors|Kia]], [[Subaru]], and others. He now heads his own firm: Teague Design<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=105333 |publisher=Edmund's Inside Line |title=Duesenberg May Hit the Streets Again |archivedate=18 April 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050418223340/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId%3D105333 |accessdate=20 April 